datasets.name: A multimodal human-computer interaction dataset for neurocognitive user state evaluation
datasets.description_clean: SENSE-42: A multimodal Human-Computer Interaction dataset from Simulated Environment for Neurocognitive User State Evaluation Overview SENSE-42 is a publicly available, multimodal dataset designed to support the study of user state monitoring during extended computer interaction sessions via neurocognitive, physiological and behavioural responses. Combining high-resolution neurophysiological recordings with behavioral and subjective data, this dataset enables research on the alternations of attention, mental/physical fatigue, cognitive workload, and related subjective indices at a very early stage. The dataset was collected from 42 participants over a 2-hour continuous interaction session, during which participants engaged in a series of designed tasks on a desktop computer with a mouse and keyboard. The experimental tasks were conducted within a fully simulated desktop operating system environment, designed to closely mimic real-world computer usage scenarios. This setup mirrors how people typically use computers in daily life. The simulated experiment program also enables the comprehensive capture of the mouse and keyboard data, synchronized with a high refresh rate monitor at 144 Hz. Recordings were collected in a noise-insulated room, minimizing external interruptions from the environment or the experimenter. The project includes both the raw dataset (available via Synapse) and the analysis codebase (available on GitHub, WIP) for replicability and reuse. Modalities and Data Contents The dataset includes multimodal signals across the following channels: Behavioural Data Participant interaction logs collected via PsychoPy, including task performance metrics, reaction times, and mouse & keyboard status per frame. Electroencephalography (EEG) 32-channel scalp EEG recordings collected with the BioSemi ActiveTwo system at 1024 Hz. EEG signals are stored in .bdf format. datasets.name: Brain Cancer
datasets.description_clean: Single-Cell RNAseq analysis of diffuse neoplastic infiltrating cells at the migrating front of human glioblastoma Organism Homo Sapiens Abstract Glioblastoma (GBM) is the most common primary brain cancer in adults and is notoriously difficult to treat because of its diffuse nature. We performed single-cell RNA sequencing (RNA-seq) on 3,589 cells in a cohort of four patients. We obtained cells from the tumor core as well as surrounding peripheral tissue. Our analysis revealed cellular variation in the tumor's genome and transcriptome. We were also able to identify infiltrating neoplastic cells in regions peripheral to the core lesions. Despite the existence of significant heterogeneity among neoplastic cells, we found that infiltrating GBM cells share a consistent gene signature between patients, suggesting a common mechanism of infiltration. Additionally, in investigating the immunological response to the tumors, we found transcriptionally distinct myeloid cell populations residing in the tumor core and the surrounding peritumoral space. Our data provide a detailed dissection of GBM cell types, revealing an abundance of information about tumor formation and migration. Overall Design Examination of cell types in human primary glioblastoma samples. Data Processing Short read trimming: Prinseq to remove short reads (-minlen 30) trim the first 10 bp on the 5’-end (-trimleft 10), trim reads with low quality on the 3’-end (-trimqualright 25) and filter low complexity reads (-lcmethod entropy \-lcthreshold 65). We used FASTQC to determine overrepresented sequences and removed those using cutadapt (-e 0.15 –m 30). We then used Prinseq to remove orphan pairs less than 30bp in length followed by removal of nextera adapters using Trim Galore (--stringency 1). Read alignment: reads were aligned to the hg19 genome with STAR using the following options (-outFilterType BySJout \--outFilterMultimapNmax 20 \--alignSJoverhangMin 8 \--alignSJDBoverhangMin 1 \--outFilterMismatchNmax 99

datasets.name: Crab-eating Macaque Brain RNA editing
datasets.description_clean: Crab-eating Macaque Brain RNA editing Adenosine-to-inosine (A-I) RNA editing represents one of the most abundant post-transcriptional RNA modification processes within the mammalian central nervous system. However, the lack of a precise and comprehensive inventory of RNA editing in non-human primate (NHP) brains hampers the exploration of A-I RNA editing in understanding the mammalian brain’s evolution and function. Here, we performed whole-genome and whole-transcriptome sequencing to identify 2,782,079 A-I editing sites in 39 anatomically defined brain regions of adult Macaca fascicularis (crab-eating macaque).

However, the lack of a precise and comprehensive inventory of RNA editing in non-human primate (NHP) brains hampers the exploration of A-I RNA editing in understanding the mammalian brain’s evolution and function. Here, we performed whole-genome and whole-transcriptome sequencing to identify 2,782,079 A-I editing sites in 39 anatomically defined brain regions of adult Macaca fascicularis (crab-eating macaque).

datasets.description_clean: The Consensus Brain Protein Coexpression (ConsensusProteinCoexpression) Study Plese cite Johnson ECB, et al, Nat Med, 2020 when referencing this work and to see additional methods pertaining to the full work. Methods for ALL Brain Tissue Cohorts Brain Tissue Samples and Case Classification Brain tissue used in this study was obtained from the autopsy collections of the Baltimore Longitudinal Study of Aging[1], Banner Sun Health Research Institute[2], Mount Sinai School of Medicine Brain Bank, Adult Changes in Thought Study, Mayo Clinic Brain Bank, Religious Orders Study and Rush Memory and Aging Project[3], University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine Brain Bank, and the Baltimore Coroner’s Office. Tissue was from the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (Brodmann Area 9 where available), or temporal cortex and precuneus regions where indicated. Human postmortem tissues were acquired under proper Institutional Review Board (IRB) protocols at each respective institution. Postmortem neuropathological evaluation of neuritic plaque distribution was performed according to the Consortium to Establish a Registry for Alzheimer’s Disease (CERAD) criteria[4], while extent of spread of neurofibrillary tangle pathology was assessed with the Braak staging system[5]. Other neuropathologic diagnoses were made in accordance with established criteria and guidelines[6, 7]. All case metadata, including age, sex, post-mortem interval, cognitive function, APOE genotype, neuropathological criteria, and disease status, are provided in Supplementary Table 1. Case classification harmonization across cohorts was performed using the following rubric: cases with CERAD 0-1 and Braak 0-3 without dementia at last evaluation were defined as control (if Braak equals 3, then CERAD must equal 0); cases with CERAD 1-3 and Braak 3-6 without dementia at last evaluation were defined as AsymAD; cases with CERAD 2-3 and Braak 3-6 with dementia at last evaluation were defined as AD. Dementia was defined as MMSE

datasets.name: Next-Generation Preclinical Models of NF1 Brain Tumours
datasets.description_clean: Next-Generation Preclinical Models of NF1 Brain Tumours Next-Generation Preclinical Models of NF1 Brain Tumours GFF - Next Generation Models Principal Investigator: Jürgen A. Knoblich, PhD Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Jürgen A. Knoblich, PhD Institution: IMBA - Institute of Molecular Biotechnology Project Description: Neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1) is a genetic condition caused by mutations in the NF1 tumor suppressor gene (TSG). Individuals with NF1 are prone to the development of benign and malignant tumors, particularly brain and nerve tumors. One of the most common of these tumors is the low-grade glioma (optic pathway glioma; OPG), which can be associated with vision loss or early onset puberty. While mouse Nf1-OPG models have been developed, they do not lend themselves well to rapid drug discovery and evaluation. For this reason, we aim to employ human cerebral organoids to develop tissue culture models of NF1-associated low grade gliomas (LGGs). Cerebral organoids represent a groundbreaking 3D culture system, initially developed in the Knoblich laboratory, which accurately models human-specific aspects of brain development. To establish next-generation tissue culture models of human NF1-LGG, specifically NF1-OPG, we propose to generate cerebral organoids, including models where the timing of NF1 loss can be monitored, as well as assembloids, which better represent human NF1-OPGs. The simplicity of this system will allow us to study the impact of NF1 mutation on brain tumor development. This proposed project has the potential to generate more accurate human models of NF1-associated LGGs amenable to rapid drug screening. NF Data Curator App

datasets.description_clean: Data description RNA extraction and library preparation Parietal lobe tissue of post-mortem brain was obtained with informed consent for research use and were approved by Washington University in St. Louis review board. RNA was extracted from frozen brain using Tissue Lyser LT and RNeasy Mini Kit (Qiagen, Hilden, Germany). RNA-seq was generated for brains from The Charles F. and Joanne Knight Alzheimer's Disease Research Center (Knight ADRC) [1]. RNA was extracted from frozen brain tissues using Tissue Lyser LT and RNeasy Mini Kit (Qiagen, Hilden, Germany) following the manufacturer’s instruction. The cDNA library was prepared with the TruSeq Stranded Total RNA Sample Prep with Ribo-Zero Gold kit (Illumina) and then sequenced by HiSeq 4000 (Illumina) using 2×150 paired end reads at McDonnell Genome Institute, Washington University in St. Louis with a mean of 58.14 ± 8.62 million reads. Number of reads and other QC metrics can be found in Table S1: Demographics and RNA technical details for GRN, C9ORF72 carriers, and control individuals in Neuronal VCP loss of function recapitulates FTLD-TDP pathology (Wani et al., 2021). RNA-seq Alignment and quantification RNA sequences were aligned to human GRCh38 primary assembly using Star [6]. We used the primary assembly and aligned reads to the assembled chromosomes, un-localized and unplaced scaffolds, and discarded alternative haploid sequences. Sequencing metrics, including coverage, distribution of reads in the genome [7], ribosomal and mitochondrial contents and alignment quality, were further obtained by applying Picard CollectRnaSeqMetrics (ver 2.8.2) to detect sample deviation. Additional QC metrics can be found in Table S1 in Neuronal VCP loss of function recapitulates FTLD-TDP pathology (Wani et al, 2021). We applied Salmon transcript expression quantification (ver 0.7.2) [11] to infer the gene expression for all samples included. We quantified the coding transcripts of Homo Sapiens included in the GENCODE reference

datasets.name: Comprehensive identification of somatic nucleotide variants in human brain tissue
datasets.description_clean: NDA Data Source: Data from Papers. Data from Papers are 'NDA Studies', which contain analyzed data from one or more NDA Collections (datasets from a grant or project).   The extent to which somatic mosaicism is pathogenic and how it can influence susceptibility to neuropsychiatric disorders is unknown. Genomic sequencing of single cells is the most direct approach for detecting somatic mosaicism in a given individual but requires large cell samples. Although bulk sequencing is potentially a productive alternative, analytic standards are lacking. Most existing approaches rely on paired sample comparisons premised on the assumption that variants will be present in one sample of an individual’s tissue and absent in the other – an assumption that may be valid for tumors undergoing clonal expansion, but not for other tissues. This study aims to establish standards for using deep bulk sequencing to identify brain mosaic SNVs for non-cancerous samples by conducting an unbiased and replicable comparison of data generation and analytical approaches. To accomplish this, samples from a human reference brain provided by the Lieber Institute for Brain Development were dissected from the cerebral cortex and distributed – along with fibroblasts lines grown from dura mater of the same individual – to multiple BSMN research groups. Individual BSMN teams extracted DNA, generated data through Whole Genome or Whole Exome Sequencing, and independently called variants in the reference brain. This was done by utilizing known germline variants of four genetically unrelated CEPH family individuals. datasets.description_clean: Brain Tumor Progression Challenge {row} {column width=2} {column} {column width=4} {column} {column width=5} ! There are registered participants. Join them now! {column} {column width=1} {column} {row} --- Overview Brain tumors are among the most researched diseases in the field of medical image computing. This is also reflected by the popularity of challenges like the MICCAI2024 BraTS Challenge, the MICCAI2024 FeTS Challenge, and the use of brain MRIs in challenges like MICCAI2024 MOOD Challenge for anomaly detection. Most research, however, focuses only on single time-points, even when evaluating longitudinal properties like disease progression. We address this significant gap in current research with the MICCAI2024 Brain Tumor Progression Challenge (BraTPRO). The goal of this challenge is the development of methods for the classification of response according to the RANO criteria from longitudinal brain tumor MRIs. RANO distinguishes four types of response between consecutive images, namely complete response, partial response, stable disease and progressive disease. During training, ground truth segmentation masks are available as additional supervision signal. The challenge is split in two tasks. In the first task, the focus is on method development for which we provide a development dataset. Submitted methods will subsequently be trained and evaluated on hidden train and test sets. For the second task, participants are free to train their models with all data available - public as well as private - and submit the trained models only for evaluation on the hidden test set. The detailed challenge description can be found on Zenodo For more information also check out Github. --- Timeline All dates are subject to change, also check the Announcements! --1. datasets.name: Hales Proteomics Paper - Detergent-Insoluble Brain Proteome
datasets.description_clean: Despite a key role of amyloid-beta (Aβ) in Alzheimer’s disease (AD), mechanisms that link Aβ plaques to tau neurofibrillary tangles and cognitive decline still remain poorly understood. The purpose of this study was to quantify proteins in the sarkosyl-insoluble brain proteome correlated with Aβ and tau insolubility in the asymptomatic phase of AD (AsymAD) and through mild cognitive impairment (MCI) and symptomatic AD. Employing label-free mass spectrometry based proteomics, we quantified 2,711 sarkosyl-insoluble proteins across the prefrontal cortex from 35 individual cases representing control, AsymAD, MCI and AD. Significant enrichment of Aβ and tau in AD was observed, which correlated with neuropathological measurements of plaque and tau tangle density, respectively. Pairwise correlation coefficients were also determined for all quantified proteins to Aβ and tau, across the 35 cases. Notably, 6 of the 10 most correlated proteins to Aβ were U1 small nuclear ribonucleoproteins (U1 snRNPs). Three of these U1 snRNPs (U1A, SmD and U1-70K) also correlated with tau consistent with their association with tangle pathology in AD. Thus, proteins that cross-correlate with both Aβ and tau, including specific U1 snRNPs, may have potential mechanistic roles in linking Aβ plaques to tau tangle pathology during AD progression. Changes in the detergent-insoluble brain proteome linked to amyloid and tau in Alzheimer's Disease progression. Proteomics. 2016 Dec;16(23):3042-3053. doi: 10.1002/pmic.201600057. PubMed PMID: 27718298; PubMed Central PMCID: PMC5462625.

datasets.name: PU.1 Enriched snRNAseq Human Brain Data from Alzheimer's and Aged Cases
datasets.description_clean: Welcome to the PU.1 enriched human brain snRNAseq dataset! Here we provide the raw, processed, and supplemental single-nucleus RNAseq (snRNAseq) data from the manuscript titled "Human microglia show unique transcriptional changes in Alzheimer’s disease" published in Nature Aging (DOI: 10.1038/s43587-023-00424-y) and available at https://www.nature.com/articles/s43587-023-00424-y. These data are snRNAseq from 22 human individual brains that have low pathology (healthy aged), or those with moderate to severe Alzheimer's disease pathology. Prior to sequencing, the samples were enriched for PU.1, a myeloid marker, that increases the number of microglia sequenced per sample. Acknowledgements: Funding for the generation of this dataset was provided by the National Institutes of Health National Institute on Aging (RF1AG063540, P30AG066509, R01AG073918) and the Weill Neurohub. Additional support was provided by the Ellison Foundation. Autopsy materials used in this study were obtained from the University of Washington Neuropathology Core, which is supported by the Alzheimer’s Disease Research Center (P50AG005136-33) and the Adult Changes in Thought Study (U01AG006781). Collaborations: We welcome you to either request access to the dataset, or to reach out to Dr. Suman Jayadev and Dr. Katherine Prater directly to discuss a collaboration and your use of this resource. 1. Data Description The PU.1 enriched human brain snRNAseq dataset contains 127,371 nuclei identified as microglia, an average of 5790 microglia per individual human. These microglia nuclei were extracted from the grey matter of the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex of aged individuals with and without Alzheimer's disease pathology. This dataset also includes the demographic, clinical, and neuropathology features of each individual sample including coded age at death, sex, APOE genotype, Alzheimer's disease neuropathic change score (ADNC), as well as individual neuropathology metrics of Thal and Braak phases and CE

Data from Labs are 'NDA Collections', which contain datasets from one grant or project.   Tourette Syndrome (TS) is a disorder of the developing telencephalon for which no significant causative genetic variant has yet emerged through the examination of blood samples. In this proposal we investigate whether somatic mutations might underlie in part the pathogenesis of TS. Existing evidence suggests that cells accumulate somatic mutations after the formation of the zygote, implying that cells of the human body do not have identical DNA sequence. datasets.description_clean: NDA Data Source: Data from Labs. Data from Labs are 'NDA Collections', which contain datasets from one grant or project.   Schizophrenia (SCZD) is a debilitating and typically incurable neuropsychiatric disease that affects 1% of the human population. Disease symptoms, which include hallucinations, paranoia, and impaired cognition, are thought to arise from impairments in neuronal connectivity and plasticity, but etiology of these defects remains unclear. Multiple lines of evidence suggest a strong genetic component to SCZD. Thus, identifying genetic variants associated with SCZD may provide critical tools for understanding and treating the disease. Indeed, recent genome wide association studies have identified >100 loci that are associated with SCZD, but these genetic variants account for only a small percentage of disease incidence. One potential explanation for this unsatisfying result is that SCZD risk alleles are not inherited through the germline, but instead arise through somatic mutations within neurons of affected individuals. Perhaps it is the propensity for somatic mosaicism that is inherited in patients with SCZD. It is now clear that somatic mosaicism of DNA sequence is much more common than previously thought (i.e., all cells within an individual do not contain the same genome), and that this phenomenon is particularly prevalent in the brain. These genomic differences may contribute to the diversity of neuronal function. However, dysregulation of processes that generate or control somatic mosaicism may lead to disease-related genomic instability. Our hypothesis, therefore, is that somatic mosaicism in neurons or their progenitors are a major contributor to SCZD pathogenesis. Gutmann Project Lead / Data Coordinator: David H. Gutmann Institution: Washington University in St. Louis Project Description: NF1-associated low-grade gliomas (LGGs) are among the most common brain tumors in children with NF1, and are a major cause of morbidity, including visual impairment. To date, there has been a paucity of humanized pre-clinical model systems for these low-grade neoplasms. In collaboration with Dr. Jürgen Knoblich (IMBA, Vienna), we have successfully developed human stem cell-derived cerebral organoids that harbor genetic alterations critical for NF1-LGG pathogenesis. In this proposal, we will significantly advance these humanized NF1-LGG models, such that they become valuable resources for the greater NF1 research community to perform basic discovery science and for pre-clinical targeted therapeutics evaluation. datasets.description_clean: Dataset Description The Eye-BCI multimodal dataset provides an extensive collection capturing simultaneous electroencephalography (EEG), electrooculogram (EOG), electromyogram (EMG), high-speed video recordings, and synchronized eye-tracking. Participants' mental states and selected physical characteristics are also included, creating a solid foundation for examining ocular artifacts and eye-movement features in Brain-Computer Interface (BCI) applications. Four experimental paradigms are recorded to elicit various sensory-motor responses and their influence on ocular activity: Motor Imagery (MI), Motor Execution (ME), Steady-State Visually Evoked Potentials (SSVEP), and P300 speller tasks. Within the P300 paradigm, trials are organized into two folders to differentiate word-length conditions, one for four-letter target words and the other for five-letter targets. Dataset information A detailed description of the dataset is available in the following paper: Guttmann-Flury, E., Sheng, X. & Zhu, X. Dataset combining EEG, eye-tracking, and high-speed video for ocular activity analysis across BCI paradigms. Sci Data 12, 587 (2025). https://doi.org/10.1038/s41597-025-04861-9 Participants A total of 31 volunteers, including both left- and right-handed individuals, participated in this experiment across 63 sessions, amounting to approximately 46 hours of recording. The dataset includes 2520 trials for each of the Motor Imagery (MI), Motor Execution (ME), and Steady-State Visually Evoked Potentials (SSVEP) paradigms, and 5670 trials for the P300 paradigm. During the initial session, participants completed a questionnaire assessing their demographic information, physiological details, and psychophysiological states. Additionally, an a priori sample size calculation was performed to ensure adequate power for the analysis of signals related to blinks as well as cortical sources activated during the different paradigms^1^. datasets.name: SPARK-Zurich Dataset - Ultra-high-field diffusion MRI and mesoSPIM microscopy of the mouse brain
datasets.description_clean: The SPARK-Zurich dataset consists of high-resolution resolution post mortem DT-MRI and 3D light-sheet microscopy data of Thy1-YFP mice. The aim of the dataset is to facilitate research for (1) optimizing DT-MRI to light-sheet microscopy image registration methods as well as (2) to validate or inform DT-MRI with ground truth information on the cellular composition of the underlying tissue. Background An ultimate goal for the understanding of brain functioning is to produce comprehensive whole-brain depictions of neuronal connectivity at the level of individual neurons and synapses. Such detailed maps would allow studying brain network organization and offer a framework for linking connectivity abnormalities to neurological and cognitive impairments in any pathology affecting the brain. Our project aims to make a step forward in this direction by directly depicting populations of Thy1 neurons in the rodent brain in 3D and using this information for validating / informing DT-MRI based visualization methods. For this research endeavor, novel methods are required that bridge the micro- and macro-scales to achieve anatomical correspondence, but also to be able to use both scales of data in the reconstruction of brain connectomics. We provide whole-brain DT-MRI data at 100 um isotropic resolution in native image coordinate space as well as transformed to the Common Coordinate Framework (CCFv3) of the Allen Mouse Brain Connectivity Atlas. datasets.name: Tinnitus
datasets.description_clean: Welcome to NBML Tinnitus Dataset! "Tinnitus" dataset contains resting-state raw EEG data recorded from tinnitus patients at National Brain Mapping Laboratory (NBML), Tehran, Iran, using a 64 channel g.HIamp biosignal amplifier and acquisition/processing system (g.tec medical engineering, Austria) (http://www.gtec.at) with the electrodes positioned according to the international 10–10 system. Impedances of the active electrode system were kept below 50k ohms during recording. The EEG signals consisting of alternating 5-min eyes-closed and 5-min eyes-open, were recorded using right ear reference (A2) electrode, sampled at 1200Hz. - The folders "Subject1" to "Subject10" contain EEG data files (.mat) for 10 tinnitus patients. - The file "Electrodenumbers.xlsx" shows the electrode, which is related to each EEG channel. - The file "ChannelLocation.txt" shows the EEG channel locations. To download the dataset, please send a request email with your Synapse username to Fahimeh Mohagheghian (fahimeh.mohagheghian@uconn.edu). Please, cite our papers if you use our data in any publication: 1. Mohagheghian, F., et al., Altered effective brain network topology in tinnitus: An EEG source connectivity analysis. Biomedical Signal Processing and Control, 2021. 64: p. 102331. 2. Mohagheghian, F., et al., Computer-aided tinnitus detection based on brain network analysis of EEG functional connectivity. Journal of Biomedical Physics & Engineering, 2019. 9(6): p. 687.

datasets.name: AI-IMPACT consortium
datasets.description_clean: AI-IMPACT (Health Holland funded): Repurposing and discovery of multi-target kinase inhibitors against brain tumors Supported by Health Holland OVERVIEW Background Cancers are traditionally treated with unspecific and rather toxic chemotherapies like cisplatin. These therapies affect healthy as well as diseased cells and cause therefore many adverse effects. More recently, new therapies have been developed that are more specific by targeting oncogenes (Luo, Solimini, & Elledge, 2009), proteins that are directly involved in tumor formation/maintenance when they are mutated (Kolch, Halasz, Granovskaya, & Kholodenko, 2015). Many oncogenes are kinase proteins such as EGFR, HER2 and BRAF and considered personalized targets. Unfortunately, drugs designed against these personalized targets are commonly prone to therapy resistance (Prados et al., 2009; Reardon et al., 2010; Saleem and Westerman et al., 2019; Sathornsumetee et al., 2010). The clinical efficacy of kinase inhibitors is often the result of poly-pharmacological action of drug molecules (i.e., the interaction of a compound with more than one target protein). It is known that at least 50% of kinase inhibitors in the clinic affect multiple targets (Kanev, de Esch, Westerman et al., 2019; Klaeger et al., 2017). Kinase inhibitors commonly inhibit between three (selumetinib) to up to sixty kinase proteins (staurosporine, dovitinib, vandetanib and dasatinib) as was convincingly revealed by partner NTRC (Uitdehaag De Man, Zaman et al., 2018). Therefore, it seems likely that both oncogene dependencies as well as non-oncogene dependencies are driving the potencies of kinase inhibitors. However, the mechanism of action of multi-target drugs is difficult to comprehend due to limited information that can be drawn from reductionistic approaches such as CRISPR-CAS9 mediated depletions of single proteins. datasets.description_clean: Two-Decades Brainclinics Archive for Insights in Neurophysiology (TD-BRAIN) link to dataset: http://www.brainclinics.com/resources Sorry for the inconvenience, you can download the dataset from this resource: http://www.brainclinics.com/resources , we are still working on getting the permissions and GDPR compliant forms up here at synapse, but it all works at our own website. You will need orcid credentials: https://orcid.org/signin, and then you should be ready to go! We present the extensive Two Decades-Brainclinics Research Archive for Insights in Neurophysiology (TD-BRAIN) EEG database. This clinical lifespan database (5-89 years) contains resting-state, raw EEG-data complemented with relevant clinical and demographic data of a heterogenous collection of 1274 psychiatric patients collected between 2001 to 2021. Main indications included are Major Depressive Disorder (MDD; N=378), attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD; N=253), Subjective Memory Complaints (SMC: N=63) and obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD; N=70). Demographic-, personality- and day of measurement data are included in the database. Thirty percent of clinical and treatment outcome data will remain blinded for prospective validation and replication purposes. datasets.name: Drug repositioning identifies digoxin as a potential therapy for groups 3 and 4 medulloblastoma
datasets.description_clean: Systems biology–based drug repositioning identifies digoxin as a potential therapy for groups 3 and 4 medulloblastoma Medulloblastoma (MB) is the most common malignant brain tumor of childhood. Although outcomes have improved in recent decades, new treatments are still needed to improve survival and reduce treatment-related complications. The MB subtypes groups 3 and 4 represent a particular challenge due to their intragroup heterogeneity, which limits the options for “rational” targeted therapies. Here, we report a systems biology approach to drug repositioning that integrates a nonparametric, bootstrapping-based simulated annealing algorithm and a 3D drug functional network to characterize dysregulated driver signaling networks, thereby identifying potential drug candidates. From more than 1300 drug candidates studied, we identified five members of the cardiac glycoside family as potentially inhibiting the growth of groups 3 and 4 MB and subsequently confirmed this in vitro. Systemic in vivo treatment of orthotopic patient-derived xenograft (PDX) models of groups 3 and 4 MB with digoxin, a member of the cardiac glycoside family approved for the treatment of heart failure, prolonged animal survival at plasma concentrations known to be tolerated in humans. These results demonstrate the power of a systematic drug repositioning method in identifying a potential treatment for MB. Our strategy could potentially be used to accelerate the repositioning of treatments for other human cancers that lack clearly defined rational targets. datasets.description_clean: Active Place Avoidance (APA) Learning – Complex Cognition. In APA tests (BioSignal Group, Brooklyn, NY) mice undergo 3 days of active place avoidance testing. Active place avoidance assesses the ability of a mouse to segregate sensory information to learn the location of stationary shock zone on a rotating arena. The shock zone location is learned by the mouse attending to relevant distal visual cues in the room while ignoring irrelevant proximal olfactory cues deposited on the arena (Wesierska M, Dockery C, Fenton AA (2005) Beyond Memory, Navigation, and Inhibition: Behavioral Evidence for Hippocampus-Dependent Cognitive Coordination in the Rat. J Neurosci 25: 2413–2419). Behavioral assessments is done in a rectangular room (4m x 3m) containing a behavioral apparatus that consists of a 40-cm diameter circular arena that rotated at 1 rpm. The room has prominent visual landmarks on the walls. A computer tracks the position of the mouse using a computer-controlled infrared Firewire camera located 1.2 m above the arena. The signal from the camera is analyzed using a spot-tracker (BioSignal Group, Brooklyn, NY). The movement of the animal relative to the arena is calculated every 33 msec from the positions of the mouse and a light emitting diode that marked the outer part of the arena. What have you appreciated about the group and what would you like to see improved? Abstract: Our goal as data visualization researchers is to create new and more effective ways to visualize and communicate the data created by scientific, engineering, and medical experiments and simulations. This process involves a combination of data abstraction, visual perception, and design. Although our data visualizations are created to communicate scientific results, some of our visualizations of computer simulations in combustion or the bioelectric activity in the heart and brain, or of data ranging from a galactic scale down to a cellular level, have also been viewed as works of art. Bio: Chris Johnson is a faculty member within and founding director of the Scientific Computing and Imaging (SCI) Institute at the University of Utah where he is a Distinguished Professor of Computer Science and holds faculty appointments in the Departments of Physics and Bioengineering. His research interests are in the areas of scientific computing and scientific visualization. With Professor Rob MacLeod, Dr. Johnson founded the SCI research group in 1992, which has since grown to become the SCI Institute employing over 200 faculty, staff and students. Professor Johnson directed SCI until 2018. Professor Johnson serves on several international journal editorial boards, as well as on advisory boards to several national and international research centers. - View his full bio - Learn about his 2013 Science and Art Exhibit at the Kimball Art Center - Check out his interactive exhibit at the Leonard Museum in Salt Lake City
